---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import UuidGeneratorIsland from '../../islands/UuidGeneratorIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('uuid-generator')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <UuidGeneratorIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Select the UUID version you need from the dropdown — <strong>v4</strong> for a random
        identifier or <strong>v7</strong> for a time-ordered identifier — then choose how many
        UUIDs to generate (1 to 100 at a time) and click <strong>Generate</strong>. Each UUID is
        copied to your clipboard with a single click.
      </p>
      <p>
        UUID v4 is the right choice for most use cases: primary keys in databases, session tokens,
        correlation IDs in distributed systems, and anywhere you need a globally unique identifier
        with no coordination between services. UUID v7 is better when you also need IDs to sort
        chronologically — for example, as database primary keys where index locality and insert
        performance matter.
      </p>
      <p>
        Generation uses your browser's <code>crypto.randomUUID()</code> API where available,
        which provides cryptographically strong randomness. No IDs are logged or stored.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between UUID v4 and UUID v7?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          UUID v4 is entirely random (122 random bits), making it suitable for any use case that
          requires uniqueness without ordering. UUID v7 embeds a Unix timestamp in the most
          significant bits, so IDs generated later sort after those generated earlier. This makes
          v7 preferable as a database primary key because sequential inserts reduce B-tree page
          splits and improve index performance.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Are UUID v4 identifiers truly unique?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          In practice, yes. A UUID v4 has 122 bits of randomness, giving approximately
          5.3 × 10<sup>36</sup> possible values. The probability of generating a duplicate even
          across billions of IDs is astronomically small — far below the likelihood of hardware
          failure causing data loss.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Can I use UUIDs as database primary keys?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes, and it is a common pattern. UUID v4 works well when you generate IDs on the client
          before an insert, or when you need IDs that are hard to guess. If you are using a
          traditional B-tree index (MySQL InnoDB, PostgreSQL), prefer UUID v7 or another
          time-ordered format to keep inserts sequential and avoid index fragmentation.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What format does a UUID use?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          A UUID is a 128-bit value displayed as 32 lowercase hexadecimal digits grouped into five
          sections separated by hyphens: <code>xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx</code>. The
          version number appears in the third section and the variant bits in the fourth section.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
